# Tor configuration for Agent Wallet — 8 isolated SOCKS5 listeners.
#
# Each anonymize leg uses a dedicated SOCKS port so its streams never
# share a circuit with another leg's. LND traffic shares 9050 with the
# boltz_submarine listener in v1; the wallet surfaces this in its
# startup gates as a known limitation operators can opt out of by
# running a second Tor instance for LND.
#
#   9050 — boltz_submarine        (also LND in single-Tor v1)
#   9051 — boltz_reverse
#   9052 — liquid
#   9053 — chain_backend
#   9054 — bip353_dns
#   9055 — quote_cache_refresh
#   9056 — chain_backend_general
#   9057 — chain_backend_anonymize
#
# IsolateDestAddr + IsolateDestPort ensure even two requests on the
# same listener to different destinations use distinct circuits.

# Defense-in-depth.
# The SocksPort bind is wildcard inside the container so any service
# on the docker network can reach it (the wallet's compose stack is
# already isolated by docker network, but a misconfigured operator
# override that publishes 9050 on the host would expose Tor without
# this allow-list). SocksPolicy below restricts accepted SOCKS
# clients to localhost + the standard RFC1918 docker bridge ranges;
# any source outside those ranges is rejected even if the bind line
# is widened later.
SocksPolicy accept 127.0.0.0/8
SocksPolicy accept 172.16.0.0/12
SocksPolicy accept 10.0.0.0/8
SocksPolicy accept 192.168.0.0/16
SocksPolicy reject *

SocksPort 0.0.0.0:9050 IsolateDestAddr IsolateDestPort IsolateSOCKSAuth
SocksPort 0.0.0.0:9051 IsolateDestAddr IsolateDestPort IsolateSOCKSAuth
SocksPort 0.0.0.0:9052 IsolateDestAddr IsolateDestPort IsolateSOCKSAuth
SocksPort 0.0.0.0:9053 IsolateDestAddr IsolateDestPort IsolateSOCKSAuth
SocksPort 0.0.0.0:9054 IsolateDestAddr IsolateDestPort IsolateSOCKSAuth
SocksPort 0.0.0.0:9055 IsolateDestAddr IsolateDestPort IsolateSOCKSAuth
SocksPort 0.0.0.0:9056 IsolateDestAddr IsolateDestPort IsolateSOCKSAuth
SocksPort 0.0.0.0:9057 IsolateDestAddr IsolateDestPort IsolateSOCKSAuth

# Persistent DataDirectory. Without this, every container
# restart resets the consensus cache + guard selections, costing
# ~60s of re-bootstrap on every restart. The /var/lib/tor volume is
# mounted from a named compose volume; growth is monitored by the
# watchdog so it doesn't surprise the operator.
DataDirectory /var/lib/tor

# Guard / circuit-build tuning. Defaults are conservative for
# general browsing; the 2026-05-21 incident's "All current guards
# excluded by path restriction type 2" warning showed that Tor's
# single-guard default leaves us wedged when that one guard can't
# satisfy a path constraint. The values below trade slightly weaker
# guard-rotation entropy for materially better recovery behaviour.
NumEntryGuards 3
GuardLifetime 6 weeks
LearnCircuitBuildTimeout 1
MaxCircuitDirtiness 600

# LongLivedPorts. The CBT learner gives circuits to these
# ports more patience before declaring them unusable. Default list
# is ssh/irc/etc; we add 8080 (LND REST) + 9735 (LN p2p) so HOLD-
# invoice payments don't trip aggressive teardowns mid-stream.
LongLivedPorts 21,22,706,1863,5050,5190,5222,5223,6523,6667,6697,8080,8332,8333,8334,9735

# SafeLogging scrubs sensitive identifiers (target addresses,
# peer fingerprints, stream IDs) from notice-level output. Operators
# often paste docker logs into bug reports; this prevents accidental
# disclosure of which onion services we contact and when.
SafeLogging 1

# Accept connections from localhost (healthcheck) and Docker bridge networks
SocksPolicy accept 127.0.0.1
SocksPolicy accept 172.16.0.0/12
SocksPolicy accept 192.168.0.0/16
SocksPolicy reject *

# Disable exit relay (we only need client functionality)
ExitRelay 0

# Reduce log noise
Log notice stderr

# Control port for the wallet's bootstrap probes,
# circuit-status reads, and the NEWNYM watchdog. Bound to
# the container network so it's reachable from sibling containers
# but not from the host (`network_mode: host` deployments must
# explicitly remap; see operator runbook).
#
# Authentication: ``HashedControlPassword`` — the
# tor-proxy/entrypoint.sh shim derives the hash from
# $TOR_CONTROL_PASSWORD at container start. If the env var is
# unset, the shim falls back to the no-auth-required boot pattern
# (still gated by SocksPolicy + container isolation). The wallet's
# control-port client at app/services/anonymize/tor.py reads the
# same plaintext password from settings.anonymize_tor_control_password
# and uses it for AUTHENTICATE.
ControlPort 0.0.0.0:9100
# The directive below is a placeholder; the entrypoint shim
# replaces it (or removes it) before exec'ing tor.
#__HASHED_CONTROL_PASSWORD_LINE__
